<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the British Medical Association (WSC085)</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the British Medical Association (WSC085)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the BMA</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> British Medical Association (BMA) represents all doctors including those working in universities and other higher education institutions who undertake research and teaching and ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> an interest in expressing our concerns at the relatively low numbers of wo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">men in this field.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are many possible reasons for the low number of women in medical academia. In order to determine which of these exerts the greatest impact, and should be addressed as a priority, it is essential that evidence is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> gathered on the career progression of women who have entered medical academia, and on the career destinations and reasons for departure of the many women who leave the sector.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:195pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The factors discouraging women from progressing to the senior levels of a me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dical academic career can be divided into those which impact all women (assumptions made about women’s abilities to carry out roles solely based upon their gender) and those which act as a discouragement to anyone (male or female) who wishes to achieve a w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ork-life balance which permits them to undertake family caring responsibilities as well as to progress in their career.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cultural issues in the Higher Education (HE) sector which prevent or deter women from entering and continuing in STEM subjects include expectations of competitiveness and excessive devotion to work.  Actions to overcome these include:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increasing the visibility of existing senior medical academic women, so that they can act as role models to inspire female medical students and trainees to embark upon and remain within an academic career; and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increasing the availability of mentoring to help advance the careers of women in the sector.  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The achievement of a work-life balance, including working part-time, should not preclude promotion. The undertaking of non-research activities (teaching, administration and pastoral roles), which can impact adversely on research profiles and career progression, should be acknowledged and valued.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A specific issue for female medical academics is the relative attractiveness of the clinical sector, especially for those who want children.  Universities should recognise previously accrued NHS service when calculating maternity allowances and enable medical academics to work part time and maintain their research profiles. Higher education institutions (HEIs) and research funders should support more flexible working patterns, better reintegration of mothers returning to work after maternity leave, and extended and affordable child-care. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mentors are key to supporting women to put themselves forward for promotion and to maintaining their self-confidence and helping to retain them in the medical academic sector.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Both the NHS and the universities should ensure that mentors are themselves properly supported and given time to undertake this task effectively.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Greater value needs to be placed on the work that female medical academics undertake.  It is often in non-traditional areas of research that do not have long-standing sources of research funding, well established career structures or dedicated subject journals in which findings can be published.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Efforts to make medical academia a more attractive place for women to work have been boosted by the National Institute for Health Research making Biomedical Research Centres and Units funding contingent on the applicant’s achievement of an Athena SWAN Silver Award.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The Government should continue to build on these methods to encourage culture change within universities.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Medical academics are doctors employed jointly by universities and the NHS, dividing their time between academic work (medical research and/or teaching, often involving elements of administration, management and pastoral care) and clinical work.  Doctors who wish to work in medical academia require a PhD or MD qualification, and trainees must achieve competency in both clinical and academic skills to complete their training, resulting in an extended training period following graduation from medical school.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Doctors’ performance in their academic role is measured in much the same way as that of wholly academic staff.  They are assessed on their research and/or teaching performance and the generation of grant funding from medical research funders. Medical academic women face the many of the same problems encountered by women working in other STEM academic departments, and similarly, there are very few senior medical academic women. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We believe that academic medicine should reflect the gender balance of those working in medicine as a whole and are concerned at the waste of talent and resources caused by female academics dropping out of academic careers. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have an ongoing project addressing the gender imbalance which exists in academic medicine.  We also contribute to the work of other bodies on this issue and monitor the progress made by higher education institutions in improving opportunities for women to progress in academic medicine. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In 2006, we produced a report on women in academic medicine with the Medical Women’s Federation (MWF) and Imperial College.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We have since followed up the report’s recommendations with medical academic organisations, produced a report on the gender pay gap in academic medicine and supported the MWF report on career breaks.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">, </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Our response draws on these reports and on anecdotal reports from our membership.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Decline of women in medical academic careers higher up the career ladder</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Despite the increasing feminisation of the medical workforce, women doctors are still strikingly under-represented in the university sector compared to their male counterparts, particularly at more senior levels. Although women have accounted for more than 40% of medical graduates in the past 20 years, only 15% of professors in medical schools are women.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are many possible reasons for the low number of women in medical academia. In our 2008 report, Women in Academic Medicine, the BMA identified a number of possible reasons for this, including:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Male domination of the recruitment process</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Working patterns</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Maternity leave</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Childcare</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research profiles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Culture.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Male domination of the recruitment process</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Academic appointment panels made up of senior academics appoint doctors to university positions. Panels are often wholly male due to the lack of women in senior positions. Despite equality training and guidelines, unconscious bias means that panels frequently have a tendency to choose appointees like themselves.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many medical academic women lack informal professional networks, in part because the low number of women in the area means that the established informal networking groups tend to be male dominated.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  Such groups have a tendency to take place at times that suit those without caring responsibilities, and those with primary responsibility for caring for their families may be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">unable to participate. Women are more likely to work part time and have less time to cultivate informal networks. As a result, they can miss out on the opportunities that men have to promote themselves and their work to colleagues and find out about academic vacancies by word of mouth: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is estimated that 70 per cent of science, engineering and technology jobs are never advertised.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Working patterns</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are more likely to work part time, generating less grant income and being more likely to encounter perceptions that they are less dedicated and less productive than full time colleagues, with the result that they are passed over for promotion.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Employers and colleagues of medical academics often do not seem to acknowledge that many effectively work only part time in each sector, spending around half their time in the NHS and the other half doing academic work.  This can generate resentment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as it is perceived that clinical academics are not doing their fair share, and because women are more likely to work part time, this is an even bigger problem for them.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Members have reported to us that the nature of certain types of research, such as laboratory research or certain clinical projects, requires highly structured, scheduled acquisition of data, over a full working week. This can preclude the participation of part time workers in such areas of study.</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Lack of accrued maternity allowance transfer between NHS and academic sector</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The majority of universities do not recognise the previous NHS service of their medical academic employees when calculating their maternity or sick leave payment entitlements. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It seems likely </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that medical academic women conclude that the NHS provides better and more secure maternity leave provision and a greater possibility of working or training part time. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Childcare</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A higher degree is essential for doctors to progress in medical academia, and doctors undertaking such qualifications are often on rates of pay or bursaries which provide them with significantly less income than they could earn if they were to work in the NHS. Women with children may find it more attractive to remain in, or return to, a clinical post in the NHS, because they will be able to purs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ue a traditional medical career and have a reliable income so that it is possible to help meet the costs of childcare. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Difficulties in developing a research profile</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are more prevalent in newly developing research areas that examine medical problems using a holistic view (i.e. take into account the effect of patients’ other health conditions and social conditions), often with cross-sector collaboration.</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Men are generally more concentrated in the established and prestigious, laboratory-based sectors, examining in detail a very specific element of disease or physiological process. Laboratory culture is often highly competitive and requires very long hours.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> It is not clear whether women are attracted to the female-dominated areas of medical research because the content of the work appeals to them more, or because the working environment and culture in which it tends to be carried out suit women better.</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">, </span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Academic performance is measured by research paper publication rates (most notably in the Research Excellence Framework (REF)). Women tend to have lower research publication rates than men.</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Established, conventional areas of research have specialist journals and funding streams.</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Doctors working in less established research areas must attempt to achieve publication of their work in generalist publications, with a greater level of competition for publication than for specialist journals.  The concentration of women working in the less established areas of research means that they can find it harder to publish their work and thus raise their academic profile.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Laboratory-based research takes a longer time to conduct than much clinical and educational research, which is reflected in its greater impact factor (the number of times a piece of research is cited by others within a specific recent timeframe) and increased likelihood of publication in prestigious journals. Researchers in lab-based areas of research can obtain higher research scores when being assessed by their universities as part of the REF process. Our members report that academics that score highly on the REF are more likely to gain promotion, and to be sought for employment by other higher education institutions (HEIs). The greater an institution’s overall REF score, the greater the amount of funding it will be allocated, so staff who help increase the REF score of an institution are more attractive as employees.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Newer areas of study are less likely to have established academic departments or corresponding academic positions within HEIs. Doctors who have specialised in a non-established area of study will have far fewer senior academic roles open to them, and find it more difficult to move institutions if the need arises. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are less likely than men to take on Principal Investigator roles</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or to be senior members of teams, being ‘more collaborative and less likely to compete at the expense of others’ (Andrews, 2002: 440).</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> There is also a tendency for women to receive less credit than men for performing the same work within a team.</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  Women also often end up carrying out non-research roles (administrative, teaching and pastoral) more often than men, reducing the time available for their research activities.</span><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> These factors impact adversely on women’s research profiles, limiting their opportunities for promotion to senior academic posts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Culture</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Men are more likely to put themselves forward for leadership/senior positions than women. For a complex set of reasons, women are more hesitant to apply for promotions.</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref39"></a><a href="#_ftn39">[39]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref40"></a><a href="#_ftn40">[40]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  There is also a tendency for women to take on pastoral (‘caring’) and administrative roles within their academic departments.</span><a name="_ftnref41"></a><a href="#_ftn41">[41]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref42"></a><a href="#_ftn42">[42]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is anecdotal evidence that men are more likely to repeatedly submit their research for publication, despite initial rejection, and women less likely to resubmit their research after </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rejection. Mentors are key to ensuring that researchers continue in their quest to achieve publication.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women in academia with mentors publish more, carry out more research and have greater career satisfaction than those without.</span><a name="_ftnref43"></a><a href="#_ftn43">[43]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are few female medical academic role models to inspire female medical students and newly qualified doctors to enter medical academia and then continue a medical academic career.</span><a name="_ftnref44"></a><a href="#_ftn44">[44]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a tendency for women to give up their job and relocate if their partners are required to move to another location. Conversely, women are less likely than men to relocate to take up positions which could further their careers if this will involve uprooting their partners and children.</span><a name="_ftnref45"></a><a href="#_ftn45">[45]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref46"></a><a href="#_ftn46">[46]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">, </span><a name="_ftnref47"></a><a href="#_ftn47">[47]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Career destination of women leaving medical academia</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst there is little systematic tracking of clinical academic career paths, the experience of our members suggests that medical academic women who decide to leave the sector transfer to wholly clinical roles within the NHS. It should be noted that many female doctors working only in the clinical sector do face challenges in progressing in their careers, but it is telling that medical academic women view these as being more easily overcome than those that they face within the academic sphere. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations to improve retention of women in medical academia and examples of good practice</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Data collection</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a lack of evidence on the reasons for the drop in the number of medical academic women at the post-PhD level. Universities and funders need to collect data to find out why they are losing medical academic women, so that they can begin to address the problem.</span><a name="_ftnref48"></a><a href="#_ftn48">[48]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref49"></a><a href="#_ftn49">[49]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Develop and implement family-friendly policies</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Organisers of research projects could consider whether tasks could be job-shared. This could also have the benefit of generating increased discussion and debate about a project, providing more insights.</span><a name="_ftnref50"></a><a href="#_ftn50">[50]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">, </span><a name="_ftnref51"></a><a href="#_ftn51">[51]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bodies with responsibility for funding or directing research could assess the drivers determining project life-spans and consider whether there is scope for project life-spans to be extended so that they do not exclude r researchers who wish to work part time. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">If universities agreed to recognise doctors’ previous accrued NHS service when calculating their maternity leave and pay and sick pay, the academic sector would become more attractive to female doctors.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Doctors with commitments that prevent them from training or working full time should be able to continue their academic careers via part time training and work opportunities. People with caring responsibilities often find it difficult to stick to a strict 9 – 5 working pattern, let alone more extended hours.  More flexible working arrangements would better support those with caring responsibilities. The increased provision of less than full time (LTFT) training (via improved accessibility, simplification of the rules governing it and standardisation between deaneries of eligibility criteria) could help more women to remain on the medical academic training track. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Academics are used to collaborating with colleagues based in other geographical locations, and this feature of academic life could be extended to enable more medical academics with caring responsibilities to continue to work. There should, therefore, be greater investment in technology that supports working from home or decreases the need for travel by enabling virtual meetings, so that medical academics can discuss issues with their colleagues, or interaction with patients. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women returning to work after maternity leave emphasise the importance of good, reliable childcare.</span><a name="_ftnref52"></a><a href="#_ftn52">[52]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> If universities could provide childcare, with extended hours and affordable even for early-career medical academics, then it is likely that more women would return to medical academia once they had had children.</span><a name="_ftnref53"></a><a href="#_ftn53">[53]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">, </span><a name="_ftnref54"></a><a href="#_ftn54">[54]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Mentoring schemes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The lack of senior women present who can offer career advice to junior women is a problem as many women will want advice from a female point of view on how best to overcome the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">challenges they can encounter working within a male-dominated environment.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The higher education sector should set up, or develop further, mentoring schemes for women in STEM subjects.  However,, senior medical academic women must not be put under greater pressure to act as mentors than their male counterparts because of their scarcity within the sector. Mentors need not always be of the same gender as their mentees or work in exactly the same subject area: clinical academics often require different mentors for the different aspects of their careers. The problems facing medical academics are often very similar to those facing women in other STEM subjects. Senior academics from any of the STEM subjects could, therefore, impart useful advice to medical academic mentees.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Medical academic women have commented that the multi-faceted nature of their roles means that they would like guidance on their clinical role, academic role and information on how to navigate career progression within their academic institutions. Potentially, they could benefit from three mentors; a senior clinician; a senior STEM academic; and a senior member of staff from any department in their university who could provide information on university committees, processes and regulations.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mentoring can be very time consuming and should be included in academic job plans, which would enable the time spent carrying out mentoring activities to be remunerated and properly credited.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Academy of Medical Sciences runs a mentoring scheme for post-doctoral clinical academic trainees, which has been widely praised throughout the medical academic sector.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref55"></a><a href="#_ftn55">[55]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The Medical Women’s Federation (MWF) has developed a ‘buddying scheme’; this is not mentoring, but a means by which senior clinicians can provide support informally to junior colleagues, with less time commitment than that entailed by mentoring.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref56"></a><a href="#_ftn56">[56]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Role models</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Organisations involved in clinical academic medicine should highlight women working in medical academia to students and junior doctors. The BMA will soon publish a document on the role of the clinical academic, including profiles of medical academic doctors, many of whom are female. The Royal Society document, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Mothers in Science: 64 ways to have it all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> also provides profiles of women in science.</span><a name="_ftnref57"></a><a href="#_ftn57">[57]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Universities could inform their female medical academic staff that such sources of information are available, perhaps in their induction to their departments and by providing links to such documents on their websites.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">At academic events and conferences, efforts should be made by organisers to invite women to be speakers and panel members. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Efforts should be made to ensure that women are invited to join or given the opportunities to be elected to the committees and groups regulating and shaping academic life.</span><a name="_ftnref58"></a><a href="#_ftn58">[58]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The involvement of women in these groups will also increase the chances of the difficulties faced by academic women to be acknowledged and addressed institutionally. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Networking</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities can set up events for medical academic women – and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women in STEM subjects – so that they can make links with the senior staff and mentors who can help them to progress in their careers. Medical schools should make more of the time spent ‘in house’ by medical students while they are still at university, and facilitate opportunities for female medical students to identify medical academic role models. Many medical schools already have mentoring systems for pastoral and/or educational purposes – these could be expanded to allow female medical students to network and gain experience and understanding in what an academic career involves. For doctors in training recruited into academic posts (such academic foundation trainees and academic clinical fellows), opportunities for female trainees to seek mentors and role models should be encouraged.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Publicising vacancies</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Medical academic roles should be advertised widely and officially.  Adverts on institutions’ own websites, in specialist journals and at other institutions will help to maximise the pool of candidates available and enable women, who may not have heard of the vacancy through networking, to apply.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Ensure women sit on academic selection panels</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">If no senior female medical academic is available to sit on an appointment panel, a woman from another STEM department, or a female member of the institution’s Human Resources department could be included. It is likely that the inclusion of women on panels will increase the chances of women being appointed to academic positions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref59"></a><a href="#_ftn59">[59]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref60"></a><a href="#_ftn60">[60]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref61"></a><a href="#_ftn61">[61]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> As the number of women in medical academia increases, the difficulty in identifying women for panels will be greatly reduced. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Help for returners </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Medical academic women have to return from maternity leave to two workplaces, clinical and academic. Universities and NHS employers are expected to jointly manage the clinical academics they employ, and together they should ensure effective and coordinated policies and schemes in place for the return to medical academic work. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities could</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> raise awareness amongst their employees of the importance of being supportive towards women returning after maternity leave, and put in place clear processes for women to report and address any problems that they encounter upon their return. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Role of Government in encouraging the retention of women in STEM careers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The requirement that departments and institutions hoping to gain National Institute for Health Research Biomedical Research Centres and Units funding must hold an Athena SWAN Silver Award has had a dramatic effect on the priority given by universities to tackling the issues which disadvantage medical academic women.</span><a name="_ftnref62"></a><a href="#_ftn62">[62]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Financial leverage appears to be an extremely effective way of encouraging institutions to take action to improve conditions for w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">omen in HEIs, and the government should build on this method to generate more success. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> British Medical Association (2008) Women in Academic Medicine. London: British Medical Association</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> The Athena SWAN Charter evolved from work between the Athena Project and the Scientific Women’s Academic Network (SWAN), to advance the representation of women in science, engineering and technology (SET). In 2011, when the Chief Medical Officer announced that the National Institute for Health Research would only expect to shortlist medical schools for biomedical research centre and unit funding if the school holds a Silver Athena SWAN award.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">Athena SWAN awards recognise and celebrate good practice in recruiting, retaining and promoting women in STEMM in higher education. The first step to gaining an award is to join the Charter. This makes higher education institutions (HEIs) eligible to apply for their own awards. HEIs must achieve a Bronze award before individual departments can apply for recognition in their own right, and potentially meet the criteria to gain a Silver Athena SWAN award. The Charter believes that a department must have institutional support and underpinning institutional good practice policies and processes in place in order to achieve and sustain an award. More information is available at </span><a href="http://www.athenaswan.org.uk/"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">www.athenaswan.org.uk/</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> British Medical Association (2008) Women in Academic Medicine. London: British Medical Association</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> British Medical Association (2009) The Pay Gap for Women in Medicine and Academic Medicine. London: British Medical Association</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> Medical Women’s Federation (2013) Career Breaks for NHS and University doctors: An analysis of the WAM database. London: Medical Women’s Federation</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> Medical Schools Council (2012) A Survey of Staffing Levels of Medical Clinical Academics in UK Medical Schools as at 31 July 2011. London: Medical Schools Council</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> Carnes M &amp; Bland C (2007) Viewpoint: A Challenge to Academic Health Centers and the National Institutes of Health to Prevent Unintended Gender Bias in the Selection of Clinical and Translational Science Award Leaders. Academic Medicine 82: 202-206.</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt"> McEwan, J (2009) Engaging women in academic medicine in the UK: report of a workshop at the Association of Physicians Annual Meeting, 2 April 2009. QJM 103: 635-639</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'T